### E4: Build-guard cross-session gating — residual risk (unaddressed)

`masonry-build-guard.js` lines 82-97: when the interrupted build was started by a prior session:
```javascript
if (buildSessionId && currentSessionId && buildSessionId !== currentSessionId) {
  process.stderr.write(`\n[Masonry] Build owned by session ${buildSessionId.slice(0, 8)}... — not blocking this session.\n`);
  process.exit(0);
}
```
The new session receives a **stderr-only** message — not injected into Claude's conversation context — and the guard exits 0. The new session is permitted to run `/plan`, `/build`, or any command freely without Stop-time enforcement. If the user dismisses the session-start resume directive, there is no secondary safety net.

Additionally, lines 92-97 handle legacy `progress.json` files with no `session_id`:
```javascript
if (!buildSessionId && currentSessionId) {
  process.stderr.write(`\n[Masonry] Build has no session owner (legacy) — not blocking this session.\n`);
  process.exit(0);
}
```
Legacy interrupted builds are silently passed through with no warning.

### E5: Stop-guard auto-commit — residual risk (unaddressed)

`masonry-stop-guard.js` lines 296-317: on orderly Stop with uncommitted session files:
```javascript
const msg = `chore: auto-commit ${staged} session file${staged !== 1 ? 's' : ''} on stop`;
execFileSync('git', ['commit', '-m', msg], { encoding: 'utf8', timeout: 10000, cwd });
```
No test-pass gate. No spec-task linkage check. No `IN_PROGRESS` task guard. All files touched by the session's Write/Edit tools are committed verbatim under a generic message with zero build traceability. Partial or broken implementations from an interrupted task can enter git history without verification.
